Enforces the project's zero-unused-dependency policy (docs/SPEC.md) by wrapping `cargo-machete` in the same offline static-check style as `cycle_check.sh`. Invoked as `machete_check.sh [ROOT=.]`, it `cd`s into `ROOT` before running.

A missing `cargo-machete` binary is a hard `FAIL` (exit 1), not a skipped check — reflecting stated policy that "no unused dependencies" must always be verified, never silently bypassed.

The interesting logic is the awk parser translating cargo-machete's grouped report format (`<crate> -- <path>/Cargo.toml:` header followed by tab-indented dep names) into one `FAIL: <path> unused dependency '<dep>'` line per dependency, printed to stderr. If cargo-machete exits nonzero but produces no line matching that shape (e.g. it can't read a manifest), the script still emits a generic `FAIL: cargo machete failed` line rather than exiting silently — this is the fallback branch guarding against format drift in cargo-machete's own output.

Exit code is 0 only if cargo-machete ran and reported zero unused dependencies; any parsed failure or unparseable error sets exit 1.